desire to belong and the impossibility of fully belonging. Meloni pays close attention to these young people’s struggles and hopes, showing us what it means to belong and to endure in contexts of social exclusion. Ways of Belonging reveals the opacities and failures of a system that excludes children from education and puts their lives in invisibility mode. An interview with the author (https://www.qmul.ac.uk/clpn/news-views/book-interviews/items/interview-with-francesca-meloni-about-her-book-ways-of-belonging-undocumented-youth-in-the-shadow-of-illegality.html)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBelonging (Social psychology)zQuébec (Province)zMontréal2DLC. 0aLatin AmericanszQuébec (Province)zMontréalxPsychology2DLC. 0aLatin AmericanszQuébec (Province)zMontréalxSocial conditions2DLC. 0aNoncitizen childrenzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxPsychology2DLC. 0aNoncitizen childrenzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxSocial conditions2DLC. 0aRight to educationzQuébec (Province)zMontréal2DLC. 0aTeenage immigrantszQuébec (Province)zMontréalxPsychology2DLC. 0aTeenage immigrantszQuébec (Province)zMontréalxSocial conditions2DLC. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aimmigration, emigration, daca, dreamers, undocumented, illegal, alien, illegal immigrant, asylum, Canada, children, child, child studies, sociology, policy, law, immigration policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079131040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197883552840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978835528423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978835528/original  a978-3-11-079131-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles